<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,1578,2030]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,317,1655,1681]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. In wing pattern, the species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[804,941,1656,1681]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatulata">
<emphasis box="[804,941,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">P. spatulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[997,1106,1656,1681]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gnoma">
<emphasis box="[997,1106,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">P. gnoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName box="[1240,1353,1656,1681]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tantilla">
<emphasis box="[1240,1353,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">P. tantilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished most easily by the short and narrow cucullus and well-developed, apically rounded juxta lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,1578,2030]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,261,1733,1759]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[277,365,1733,1759]" captionStart="FIGURES 32 – 36" captionStartId="14.[151,273,1598,1622]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,197,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,197,1575]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 32 – 36. Adults of Perittia species. 32, P. gnoma sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: 000005176; 33, P. falciferella sp. n., female, paratype. Specimen ID: 000005180; 34, P. spatulata sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: 000005159; 35, P. spatulata sp. n., female, paratype. Specimen ID: 000005172; 36, P. tantilla sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5148. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189258/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[332,365,1733,1759]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="36.0">36</number>
</figureCitation>
). Forewing length 2.2 mm; wingspan 5.3 mm (n= 
<number box="[963,974,1733,1759]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1.0">1</number>
). Head: Vertex and neck tuft yellowish white, some scales with brownish tips; background layer of frons white with some metallic lustre intermixed with brown and brown-tipped scales; labial palpus very short, straight with sharp apex, directed lateroventrally, nearly invisible; scape slightly broader than flagellum, covered with dirty-white scales with brownish tips; flagellum rather broad, ochreous grey. Thorax and tegula brownish grey, slightly mottled due to darker tips of scales. Forewing greyish brown, weakly mottled by darker tips of scales, with two costal and two dorsal yellowish-white spots. Fringe brownish grey with irregularly scattered blackish brown-tipped scales. Hindwing including fringe beige grey.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,487]" box="[197,426,151,178]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,295,151,177]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,487]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,378,190,216]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[396,543,190,216]" captionStart="FIGURES 50 – 51" captionStartId="21.[151,270,1505,1529]" captionTargetBox="[418,1156,575,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[396,1191,542,1481]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 50 – 51. Perittia tantilla sp. n., male genitalia, holotype. 50, general view; 51, uncus and gnathos in glycerol before permanent mounting in Euparal. Gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 476, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5148. Scale bar 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189263/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Figs. 
<number box="[464,543,190,216]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="50.51">50, 51</number>
</figureCitation>
). Uncus short, posterior margin weakly sclerotized. Basal arms of gnathos fused; spinose knob of gnathos slightly wider than long, tapered towards apex. Valva short and broad; sacculus weakly concave, tapering into short and narrow cucullus, tip of cucullus with two or three short but stout setae; costa distally with small hump; transtilla strongly sclerotized. Ventral shield of juxta two times longer than broad; dorsal shield of juxta triangularly-shaped, strongly sclerotized; juxta lobes well developed, weakly sclerotized, apically rounded. Digitate processes not developed. Vinculum U-shaped, strongly sclerotized. Phallus short, about five times longer than broad, vesica with six large cornuti and numerous tiny, elongate spines slightly increasing in size distally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189263/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" targetBox="[418,1156,575,1454]" targetPageId="21">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,1505,1597]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,351,1505,1529]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">FIGURES 50–51.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[358,524,1505,1528]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tantilla" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[358,524,1505,1528]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Perittia tantilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[532,592,1505,1529]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[532,592,1505,1529]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, male genitalia, holotype. 50, general view; 51, uncus and gnathos in glycerol before permanent mounting in Euparal. Gen. prep. MRAC/KMMA 0 0 476, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5148. Scale bar 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1648,2022]" box="[197,427,1648,1674]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,289,1648,1674]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Biology</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1648,2022]" box="[197,1152,1686,1713]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,360,1686,1712]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Flight period</emphasis>
. The only known specimen was captured in the beginning of April.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1648,2022]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,1725,1751]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Distribution</emphasis>
. So far this species is known only from Kakamega Forest in the Western Province of 
<collectingCountry box="[1359,1436,1725,1751]" name="Kenya" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Kenya</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,243,1764,1790]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1176,1200]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,297,1155]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,297,1155]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Collecting localities in Kenya. 1, Arabuko Sokoke Forest National Park; 2, Aberdares National Park; 3, Hell’s Gate National Park; 4, Kakamega Forest National Reserve." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189249/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Figs. 
<number box="[226,243,1764,1790]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="4.15">4</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[255,287,1764,1790]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="6.[151,259,1145,1169]" captionTargetBox="[409,1178,212,1101]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[390,1196,194,1121]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 15. Collecting localities of Elachistinae species in Kenya: 1, Arabuko Sokoke Forest National Park; 2, Aberdares National Park; 3, Hell's Gate National Park; 4, Kakamega Forest National Reserve." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189252/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1648,2022]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,330,1802,1828]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[863,959,1803,1828]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">tantillus</emphasis>
(so small) in reference to the very small size of the moth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1648,2022]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1436,152,216]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,316,1880,1906]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Remarks</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[390,498,1880,1906]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">holotype</typeStatus>
is in poor condition; the forewings are somewhat rubbed and therefore the description is approximate. This species, along with 
<taxonomicName box="[776,915,1919,1944]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatulata">
<emphasis box="[776,915,1919,1944]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">P. spatulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[974,1084,1919,1944]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gnoma">
<emphasis box="[974,1084,1919,1944]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">P. gnoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, differs from all other known species of 
<taxonomicName box="[277,421,1957,1983]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Elachistinae">Elachistinae</taxonomicName>
by the direction of the spines on the apical knob of the gnathos (see description of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gnoma">
<emphasis box="[1414,1429,1958,1983]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,231,1996,2021]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">gnoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
above). According to our observations the species 
<taxonomicName box="[841,999,1996,2021]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falciferella">
<emphasis box="[841,999,1996,2021]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">P. falciferella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1058,1173,1996,2021]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tantilla">
<emphasis box="[1058,1173,1996,2021]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">P. tantilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
considerably differ in external morphology. Therefore, in this treatment, we present them as two distinct species. However, future molecular studies might more clearly reveal their relationship.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
